#compdef chpl
# =============================================================================
# chpl — Cray/HPE's CHAPEL COMPILER — the official compiler
#         for the Chapel programming language, an open-source
#         productive parallel programming language designed for
#         high-performance computing.  Chapel began at Cray Inc.
#         (now Hewlett Packard Enterprise) as part of DARPA's
#         HPCS (High Productivity Computing Systems) program in
#         2003 — the same DARPA initiative that produced
#         Fortress (Sun, defunct) and X10 (IBM).  Chapel is the
#         survivor.  Distinguishing language features:
#           - FIRST-CLASS PARALLELISM: `forall i in 1..n do
#             A[i] = compute(i);` parallelizes by default
#             across all available threads/locales
#           - DATA LOCALITY VIA LOCALES: explicit notion of a
#             "locale" (a node in the cluster), with `on
#             Locales[i] { ... }` constructs to control where
#             computation happens
#           - DISTRIBUTED ARRAYS: arrays automatically
#             partitioned across cluster nodes via Block/Cyclic/
#             BlockCyclic/Stencil distributions
#           - ATOMICS + SYNC VARIABLES: built-in atomic types
#             (atomic int, atomic bool) + sync variables (one-
#             reader one-writer hand-off pattern for inter-task
#             synchronization)
#           - TYPE INFERENCE: most types inferred without
#             annotations
#           - GENERICS via FORMAL TYPE PARAMETERS
#           - ITERATORS as first-class language constructs
#             (separate from functions)
#           - C/Fortran INTEROP: directly call C functions +
#             Fortran subroutines from Chapel programs
#           - GPU SUPPORT (Chapel 2.0+): `--gpu nvidia` /
#             `--gpu amd` compile kernels to GPU; `forall i in
#             1..n` runs on GPU when GpuLocale is targeted
#         Used at major HPC sites for scientific computing
#         workloads: NCAR, ORNL, LANL, NERSC, NASA.  Chapel 2.0
#         (released October 2023) marked the language as
#         "production stable" with frozen syntax/semantics.
#
# Author:  Chapel Language Project — Brad Chamberlain (lead
#          language designer, Cray/HPE) + Chapel team at HPE
#          (formerly Cray Inc.) + open-source contributors
#          worldwide.  Chapel originated at Cray Inc. as part
#          of DARPA HPCS (2003-2013), then continued as open
#          source under Cray (acquired by HPE in 2019).  Brad
#          Chamberlain has been on the project from the start
#          and remains lead today.
# Source:  https://github.com/chapel-lang/chapel
#          https://github.com/chapel-lang/chapel/blob/main/compiler/main/arg.cpp
#          https://github.com/chapel-lang/chapel/blob/main/compiler/main/driver.cpp
# CLI:     compiler/main/arg.cpp — implements the
#          `ArgumentDescription` struct + parser, descended
#          from John Plevyak's IFA (Iterative Flow Analysis)
#          `arg.cc` released on SourceForge 1992-2006 under
#          MIT.  The `arg_desc[]` array in driver.cpp declares
#          ~250 flags grouped into ~15 categories using a
#          fixed-shape 8-element struct: `{long_name, short_char,
#          arg_name, description, type, value_pointer, env_var,
#          callback_function}`.
# Library: ArgumentDescription (Chapel/IFA arg.cpp)
#          ("Plevyak/IFA argument description parser" — John
#           Plevyak's IFA framework included an `arg.cc` argv
#           parser using a TABLE-DRIVEN ARGUMENT DESCRIPTION
#           model that pre-dates GNU getopt_long's argp by
#           several years.  Chapel adopted + extended this
#           parser when forking from IFA in 2004.  The
#           ArgumentDescription struct has 8 fields encoding
#           flag name, short char, value placeholder, help
#           text, argument-type code (single-char: 'F' bool
#           flag, 'N' negatable bool, 'n' positive-only bool,
#           'S' string, 'I' integer, 'P' filesystem path, 'X'
#           hex), value-storage pointer, environment-variable
#           name, and optional callback function pointer.)
# License: Apache-2.0 (Chapel); MIT-style (IFA arg.cc heritage)
# Status:  Chapel — 1998+ stars on chapel-lang/chapel; active
#          development at HPE; Chapel 2.0 released October 2023
#          marking production stability; semi-annual releases
#          since 2024 (versions 2.1 through current).  Used in
#          production HPC at major US national labs (NCAR,
#          ORNL, LANL) and EU HPC centers.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 77TH LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy welcomes
# its 77TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE — CHAPEL (Cray/HPE, 2003-present) —
# and its FIRST documented Chapel CLI mechanism: the Plevyak/IFA-
# descended ArgumentDescription struct + table-driven argv parser
# from compiler/main/arg.cpp.
# Taxonomy now spans 316 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 77 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R574 Rust=51 pico-args/vaultwarden →
# R575 Go=51 gookit/color/trdl → R576 TS-Node=51 consola/toon)
# followed by 1 NEW LANGUAGE (R577 Chapel THIS).  Leaderboard
# unchanged: Rust=51, Go=51, TypeScript-Node=51 (three-way tie
# at 51 since R576).
#
# Chapel is DISTINCT from every other documented language by being
# a PARALLEL-FIRST language designed under DARPA's HPCS initiative.
# The DARPA HPCS competition (2002-2013) funded three competing
# parallel-programming-language projects:
#   - Cray Inc.: CHAPEL (this) — only survivor still in active
#                                  development
#   - Sun Microsystems: FORTRESS — discontinued 2012 after
#                                    Oracle dropped support
#   - IBM: X10 — discontinued ~2019 after IBM defunded
# Chapel's survival reflects HPE's continued investment + the
# Chapel team's responsiveness to HPC user feedback over 20+
# years of development.
#
# The taxonomy now documents Chapel as the FIRST parallel-first
# language.  Other documented languages (Pony R??? lutra, Cray
# X10 conceptually) have concurrency but not first-class
# parallelism with explicit locale + distributed-array support.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS CHAPEL AND WHY IS IT THE 77TH LANGUAGE?
#
# Chapel is a parallel, object-oriented, productivity-focused
# programming language designed for high-performance computing.
# Distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. PARALLELISM AS A FIRST-CLASS LANGUAGE FEATURE — Chapel's
#      core syntax has explicit parallel constructs:
#
#          // Data parallelism: forall expression
#          forall i in 1..n with (ref A) do
#              A[i] = compute(i);
#
#          // Task parallelism: cobegin block
#          cobegin {
#              compute_left();
#              compute_right();
#              compute_center();
#          }
#
#          // Coforall: forall with task spawning
#          coforall task in 1..numTasks {
#              workQueue.process(task);
#          }
#
#          // begin: spawn unsynchronized task
#          begin compute_background();
#
#      Every loop, every block can be parallelized with a
#      keyword change.  Compare:
#         * C/C++: OpenMP pragmas (require parallel-aware compiler)
#         * Rust: rayon library (third-party)
#         * Go: goroutines + channels (concurrency, not parallelism)
#         * Chapel: forall/coforall/cobegin/begin AS LANGUAGE KEYWORDS
#      FIRST documented language with parallelism as core
#      language keywords (not library, not pragma).
#
#   2. LOCALES + DATA-LOCAL EXECUTION — Chapel has an explicit
#      "locale" abstraction representing a compute resource
#      (cluster node, GPU, multi-socket NUMA region).  Programs
#      reason about WHERE code runs via `on` clauses:
#
#          on Locales[3] {
#              // Code runs on locale 3 of the cluster
#          }
#
#          // Distributed array partitioned across locales
#          var A: [1..n] real dmapped Block(boundingBox={1..n});
#
#          // Forall iterates with data locality
#          forall a in A {
#              // Each iteration runs on the locale OWNING a
#          }
#
#      Distributions include Block, Cyclic, BlockCyclic, Stencil,
#      ReplicatedDist, and user-defined.  Compare:
#         * C/C++: MPI for distributed (explicit message passing)
#         * Java: RMI (manual)
#         * Erlang: process distribution (similar concept but
#                    actor-based)
#         * Chapel: LOCALE as first-class language abstraction
#                    with `on` clauses
#      FIRST documented language with locale-based distributed-
#      memory abstraction as core language feature.
#
#   3. SYNC VARIABLES + ATOMIC TYPES — Chapel built-in concurrent-
#      programming primitives:
#
#          var s: sync int;          // sync variable
#          var a: atomic int;        // atomic integer
#
#          // sync write/read protocol:
#          s.writeXF(42);            // write to empty/Full
#          var x = s.readFE();       // read from full/Empty
#
#          // atomic operations:
#          a.add(1);
#          a.compareExchange(0, 1);
#
#      Compare:
#         * Java: java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger
#         * C++: std::atomic<int> + std::mutex
#         * Chapel: sync (handoff) + atomic (lock-free) as
#                    PRIMARY TYPES with single-keyword declarations
#
#   4. ITERATORS AS LANGUAGE CONSTRUCT — Chapel iterators are
#      DIFFERENT from functions: they YIELD values across calls,
#      can be PARALLEL (yield from multiple tasks concurrently),
#      can be FOLLOWER (composable with other iterators):
#
#          iter fibonacci(n: int): int {
#              var a = 0, b = 1;
#              for i in 1..n {
#                  yield a;
#                  (a, b) = (b, a + b);
#              }
#          }
#
#          iter parallelRange(r: range): int {
#              forall i in r do yield i * 2;
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * Python: yield in functions (generators)
#         * C#: yield return (IEnumerable)
#         * Rust: Iterator trait (more explicit)
#         * Chapel: iter keyword distinct from func, with
#                    PARALLEL iterator variants
#
#   5. GPU SUPPORT (since 2.0) — Chapel programs can run on
#      GPUs by targeting GpuLocale:
#
#          on here.gpus[0] {
#              forall i in 1..n do A[i] = compute(i);
#              // Compiles to NVIDIA CUDA or AMD ROCm kernels
#          }
#
#      Compile with `chpl --gpu nvidia program.chpl` or
#      `chpl --gpu amd program.chpl`.  No separate kernel
#      syntax — the same `forall` becomes a GPU kernel when
#      executed on a GpuLocale.  Compare:
#         * CUDA C++: separate __global__ kernels with launch syntax
#         * OpenCL: separate kernel files
#         * SYCL: separate kernel functors
#         * Chapel: SAME LANGUAGE syntax for CPU + GPU; locale
#                    placement determines execution
#      FIRST documented language with same-syntax CPU + GPU
#      execution via locale dispatch.
#
#   6. C/FORTRAN INTEROP AS LANGUAGE FEATURE — Chapel can
#      directly call C and Fortran routines:
#
#          require "fortran_lib.h";
#          extern "BLAS_ROUTINE" proc dgemm(...);
#
#          extern proc strlen(s: c_string): c_int;
#          var len = strlen(c"hello");
#
#      Plus the `c_array`/`c_ptr`/`c_string`/`c_int` types
#      bridge Chapel ↔ C ABI cleanly.  Critical for HPC where
#      decades of Fortran/C numerical libraries exist (BLAS,
#      LAPACK, FFTW, MPI, etc).
#
# Use cases for Chapel:
#   * Scientific HPC computing at national labs (climate models,
#     molecular dynamics, particle physics simulations)
#   * Graph algorithms at scale (Chapel's HPCC RandomAccess
#     and SSCA2 benchmark implementations are competitive)
#   * Distributed array computations (analogous to NumPy/Julia
#     for HPC scale)
#   * GPU computing as an alternative to CUDA C++ when same-
#     source CPU+GPU execution is valuable
#   * Teaching parallel programming concepts (Chapel's
#     readable syntax + explicit parallelism keywords make it
#     pedagogically clean)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE chpl CLI — Plevyak/IFA ArgumentDescription table-driven parser
#
# chpl's argv parser is in compiler/main/arg.cpp + driver.cpp.
# The `arg_desc[]` array in driver.cpp declares ~250 flags
# using 8-tuple ArgumentDescription records:
#
#     static ArgumentDescription arg_desc[] = {
#         {"", ' ', NULL, "Module Processing Options", NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL},
#         {"count-tokens", ' ', NULL,
#             "[Don't] count tokens in main modules", "N",
#             &countTokens, "CHPL_COUNT_TOKENS", NULL},
#         {"main-module", ' ', "<module>",
#             "Specify entry point module", "S256",
#             NULL, NULL, setMainModuleName},
#         {"module-dir", 'M', "<directory>",
#             "Add directory to module search path", "P",
#             NULL, NULL, addModulePath},
#         // ... ~250 more entries ...
#         {0}
#     };
#
# Struct fields (in order):
#   1. long_name          ("count-tokens", "main-module", ...)
#   2. short_char         ('M', 'I', 'L', 'o', 'l', 'O', 'g', 'h')
#   3. arg_placeholder    ("<directory>", "<module>", NULL)
#   4. description        help text (with [Don't] for negatable)
#   5. type code:
#        "F"  boolean flag (always-on)
#        "N"  negatable boolean (--flag / --no-flag)
#        "n"  inverse boolean (default ON; --no-flag turns OFF)
#        "S"  string
#        "S256" string with max length 256
#        "I"  integer
#        "P"  filesystem path
#        "X"  hex value (e.g., dyno-break-on-hash)
#   6. value_pointer      address of static variable to fill
#   7. env_var            environment variable that backs flag
#   8. callback           optional function called when flag matched
#
# Category headers (rows with empty long_name) group flags
# into ~15 sections:
#   - Module Processing Options
#   - Warning and Language Control Options
#   - Parallelism Control Options
#   - Debugging Control Options
#   - Optimization Control Options
#   - Run-time Semantic Check Options
#   - Code Generation Options
#   - Code Compilation Options
#   - LLVM Code Generation Options
#   - C Code Generation Options
#   - Compilation Trace Options
#   - Miscellaneous Options
#   - Compiler Configuration Options
#   - Compiler Information Options
#   - Developer Flags (suppressed unless --devel)
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented argv parser:
#
#   1. TABLE-DRIVEN 8-TUPLE ARGUMENTDESCRIPTION — Every other
#      documented argv parser uses chained builders, struct
#      tags, or declarative configs.  Chapel's ArgumentDescription
#      uses a flat 8-field tuple table.  FIRST documented argv
#      parser with explicit 8-tuple flag declaration.
#
#   2. PLEVYAK/IFA HERITAGE — Every other documented argv parser
#      was designed within the last 15 years.  Chapel's parser
#      descends from John Plevyak's IFA (Iterative Flow
#      Analysis) framework from 1992-2006 SourceForge era —
#      predating GNU argp, predating Boost.Program_options.
#      FIRST documented argv parser with pre-2006 academic-
#      tool genealogy.
#
#   3. TYPE-CODE SINGLE-CHAR ENCODING — Every other documented
#      argv parser uses type names ("string", "int") or Go/Rust
#      type identifiers.  Chapel encodes types as SINGLE CHARS
#      ('F', 'N', 'n', 'S', 'S256', 'I', 'P', 'X').
#      FIRST documented argv parser with single-char type
#      encoding.
#
#   4. EVERY FLAG HAS ENV-VAR BACKING — Most flags in arg_desc[]
#      have an env-var name (CHPL_*) that backs them.  Chapel
#      users can set environment variables to override defaults
#      across runs.  Compare:
#         * goflags (R563): chainable .EnvVar() method, opt-in
#         * Chapel: env-var backing in the SAME flag declaration
#                    (field 7 of the 8-tuple)
#      FIRST documented argv parser with env-var backing as
#      mandatory declaration field.
#
#   5. CATEGORY HEADERS AS EMPTY-NAME ROWS — Most argv parsers
#      group flags via separate metadata (kingpin's createGroup
#      function, clap's Groups).  Chapel inlines category
#      headers in the SAME flat array as flags — rows with
#      empty long_name are headers.  FIRST documented argv
#      parser with inline category headers in the flag table.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (selected high-impact subset sourced
# directly from https://github.com/chapel-lang/chapel/blob/main/
# compiler/main/driver.cpp arg_desc[] array.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s \
    '(- *)--copyright[show copyright]' \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[help (show flag list)]' \
    '(- *)--help-env[show environment variable help]' \
    '(- *)--help-settings[show current flag settings]' \
    '(- *)--license[show license]' \
    '(- *)--print-chpl-home[print CHPL_HOME and exit]' \
    '(- *)--print-chpl-loc[print this executable'\''s path and exit]' \
    '(- *)--version[show version]' \
    '(-o --output)'{-o+,--output=}'[name output executable]:file:_files' \
    '(-O --optimize)'{-O,--optimize}'[optimize generated code]' \
    '--no-optimize[disable code optimization]' \
    '--fast[disable checks; optimize/specialize code]' \
    '--baseline[disable all Chapel optimizations]' \
    '(-g --debug-symbols)'{-g,--debug-symbols}'[generate debug symbols]' \
    '--debug[compile in best way for debugging]' \
    '--checks[enable all runtime checks]' \
    '--no-checks[disable all runtime checks]' \
    '--bounds-checks[enable bounds checking]' \
    '--no-bounds-checks[disable bounds checking]' \
    '--div-by-zero-checks[enable divide-by-zero checks]' \
    '--no-div-by-zero-checks[disable divide-by-zero checks]' \
    '--cast-checks[enable safeCast value checks]' \
    '*'{-I+,--hdr-search-path=}'[C header search path]:directory:_directories' \
    '*'{-L+,--lib-search-path=}'[C library search path]:directory:_directories' \
    '*'{-l+,--lib-linkage=}'[C library linkage]:library:' \
    '*'{-M+,--module-dir=}'[add directory to module search path]:directory:_directories' \
    '--main-module=[specify entry point module]:module:' \
    '--edition=[specify the language edition]:edition:(pre-edition 2024 2024.1 2025 2025.1 latest)' \
    '*'{-s+,--set=}'[set config value (name[=value])]:name=value:' \
    '--ccflags=[back-end C compiler flags]:flags:' \
    '--ldflags=[back-end C linker flags]:flags:' \
    '--mllvm=[LLVM flags]:flags:' \
    '--static[generate statically linked binary]' \
    '--dynamic[generate dynamically linked binary]' \
    '--specialize[specialize generated code for CHPL_TARGET_CPU]' \
    '--codegen[do code generation]' \
    '--no-codegen[skip code generation (compile-only)]' \
    '--savec=[save generated C code in directory]:directory:_directories' \
    '--local[target one locale]' \
    '--no-local[target many locales (distributed)]' \
    '--detailed-errors[enable detailed error messages]' \
    '--warn-unstable[enable warnings for in-flux language features]' \
    '--no-warnings[disable warning output]' \
    '*--explain-call=[explain resolution of call (func[:module][:line])]:call spec:' \
    '*--explain-instantiation=[explain instantiation of function or type]:spec:' \
    '--print-commands[print system commands]' \
    '--print-passes[print compiler passes]' \
    '--print-passes-file=[print compiler passes to file]:file:_files' \
    '--print-passes-memory[print memory usage after each pass]' \
    '--print-callgraph[print a representation of the callgraph]' \
    '--print-callstack-on-error[print Chapel call stack on errors]' \
    '--print-search-dirs[print module search path]' \
    '--print-module-files[print module file locations]' \
    '--devel[compile as a developer (enables --devel flags)]' \
    '--home=[path to Chapel'\''s home directory]:directory:_directories' \
    '--gpu=[specify GPU vendor]:gpu:(nvidia amd cpu)' \
    '--target-arch=[target architecture]:arch:' \
    '--target-cpu=[target CPU model for specialization]:cpu:' \
    '--target-platform=[platform for cross-compilation]:platform:' \
    '--target-compiler=[compiler for generated code]:compiler:(gnu clang llvm intel cray)' \
    '--target-mem=[memory manager]:mem:(cstdlib jemalloc tcmalloc)' \
    '--locale-model=[locale model]:model:(flat numa apu gpu)' \
    '--comm=[communication implementation]:comm:(none gasnet ofi ugni mpi)' \
    '--comm-substrate=[communication conduit]:conduit:(udp ibv ucx aries ofi mpi-conduit)' \
    '--tasks=[tasking implementation]:tasks:(qthreads fifo)' \
    '--launcher=[how to launch programs]:launcher:(amudprun aprun gasnetrun_ibv gasnetrun_mpi mpirun pals slurm-gasnetrun_ibv slurm-srun ssh)' \
    '--timers=[timer implementation]:timer:(generic)' \
    '--atomics=[atomics implementation]:atomics:(intrinsics locks)' \
    '--gmp=[GMP library version]:gmp:(none bundled system)' \
    '--re2=[RE2 library version]:re2:(none bundled)' \
    '--hwloc=[whether to use hwloc]:hwloc:(none bundled system)' \
    '--sanitize-exe=[sanitizer for executable]:sanitizer:(address thread undefined memory)' \
    '--make=[make utility for generated code]:make:_command_names' \
    '*:Chapel source file:_files -g "*.chpl"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
